      {
        "id": 98,
        "name": "makegeneve",
        "username": "makegeneve",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.oshwa.org/makegeneve/{size}/43_1.png",
        "created_at": "2015-06-08T16:52:44.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I vote for self-certification.</p>\n<p>However, in the spirit of openness, we could create a certification process that is essentially a form that requires filling in with the link to the relevant documents.  For example:</p>\n<p>Parts List is Open and available at: <a href=\"http://example.com/myproduct/partslist\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">example.com/myproduct/partslist</a><br>\nSchematic is Open and available at:  <a href=\"http://example.com/myproduct/schematic\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">example.com/myproduct/schematic</a><br>\nSchematic uses AAA software<br>\nPCB design is open, using BBB software and available at : <a href=\"http://example.com/myproduct/pcb\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">example.com/myproduct/pcb</a></p>\n<p>Essentially, the OSHWA guidelines as a fillable form with links to the documentation.  With an extra level if an independent person/company has successfully built the piece of hardware.</p>\n<p>In a few years, after we\u2019ve seen the success of this process, we can open it up for independent certification bodies around the world to run the certification process, but for now let\u2019s keep it simple and accessible for all.</p>",
