      {
        "id": 107,
        "name": "abetusk",
        "username": "abetusk",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.oshwa.org/abetusk/{size}/42_1.png",
        "created_at": "2015-06-08T21:08:29.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p><a class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/david\">@david</a>, certification does come with extra assurances.  If the offending party failed to comply with the definition of open source hardware but still claimed to be certified, they could open themselves up to litigation.</p>\n<p>Self-certification allows for projects to describe themselves as open source without explicit consent while still retaining the ability to address bad actors who use the certification without being open source hardware.</p>",
